This paper deals with the problem of optimal user-network association in a hybrid cell consisting of both WLAN and UMTS networks. This problem is related to network optimization and game theory, which are subfields of computer science. Specifically, the paper considers the trade-off between financial gain and network throughput in the globally optimal association problem, which falls under the category of network optimization (cs.NI). The paper also formulates the problem as a non-cooperative dynamic game in the individual optimality case, which is a topic in game theory (cs.GT). Additionally, the paper uses dynamic programming to solve the globally optimal association problem, which is a technique in information theory (cs.IT) and control systems (cs.SY). Finally, the paper discusses the impact of Poisson arrival rate of mobiles on the threshold policy curve, which is related to multimedia systems (cs.MM).
